y during the last two decades to investigate how taxes affect a range of household behavior, including labor-force participation, saving behavior, choice of health insurance plan, choice of child care arrangements, portfolio choice, and tax evasion. They also present new analytical results on the effects of different types of tax policy. All of this research relies on household-level data-drawn either from public-use tax return files or from large household-level surveys-to explore various aspects of the relationship between taxes and household behavior. As debates about the effects of proposed tax reforms continue in the 1990s, this volume will be of interest to policy makers and scholars in the field of public finance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aFeldstein, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPoterba, James M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226241906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226241906.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles